so we decided not to spend any time covering instant games during this session.

82
00:05:18,134 --> 00:05:21,756
For our first topic of the day, we turn to the level-based progression genre.

83
00:05:23,617 --> 00:05:25,819
So in the heyday of Facebook Canvas business,

84
00:05:25,959 --> 00:05:31,162
the North American market was divvied up by the likes of Zynga, Playfish, Playdom, and CrowdStar.

85
00:05:31,902 --> 00:05:34,584
But there was a company in Istanbul called Peak Games.

86
00:05:35,381 --> 00:05:38,362
And while they weren't making many inroads in the English-speaking world,

87
00:05:39,022 --> 00:05:43,683
they were a very successful publisher across Turkey, Africa, and the Middle East.

88
00:05:45,483 --> 00:05:48,804
Well, Peak Games' minimal impact in North America changed dramatically

89
00:05:48,844 --> 00:05:52,865
with the 2015 release of a level-based progression game called Toy Blast.

90
00:05:54,085 --> 00:05:58,567
This is a sub-genre of puzzle progression, which I generally refer to as block removal.

91
00:05:59,239 --> 00:06:03,462
The player simply clicks or taps on a group of two or more light-colored blocks to remove them,

92
00:06:03,922 --> 00:06:07,185
and then the remaining blocks fall into place in the resulting gaps.

93
00:06:08,446 --> 00:06:12,188
Personally, I first saw this mechanic in a retail box game called Breakthrough,

94
00:06:12,709 --> 00:06:15,531
released by Spectrum HoloByte in the mid-1990s,

95
00:06:16,111 --> 00:06:18,553
although there might be even earlier Asian precursors.

96
00:06:19,874 --> 00:06:21,935
There are three main variants of this mechanic.

97
00:06:22,516 --> 00:06:26,418
One, exhibited here in a venerable game house game called Collapse,

98
00:06:26,919 --> 00:06:28,040
adds an arcadey aspect.

99
00:06:29,016 --> 00:06:33,158
As you click to remove parts of the wall, this row at the bottom of the screen is filling.

100
00:06:34,038 --> 00:06:38,800
Once it fills, it rises into the playing area, pushing the wall upward by a row.

101
00:06:39,520 --> 00:06:43,262
You keep playing until one of the columns reaches the top of the screen, and you lose.

102
00:06:45,062 --> 00:06:50,325
The second variant is more strategic and puzzly, as exhibited by King's Pet Rescue Saga on

103
00:06:50,345 --> 00:06:55,046
the right, and Pogo's Pop It on the left, in which gravity is turned upside down, but

104
00:06:55,087 --> 00:06:56,767
which otherwise is exactly the same game.

105
00:06:57,711 --> 00:07:00,173
In this variant, no blocks are added as you play.

106
00:07:00,693 --> 00:07:03,295
You just plan your moves to remove as many as possible.

107
00:07:04,556 --> 00:07:09,040
And the third variant, of which Toy Blast is an example, as blocks are removed, more

108
00:07:09,080 --> 00:07:13,483
blocks fall in from the top of the screen to replace them, just like in popular match

109
00:07:13,503 --> 00:07:15,665
three games such as Bejeweled and Candy Crush.

110
00:07:16,666 --> 00:07:21,489
The gameplay revolves around a goal, or set of goals, for each level, and then a limited

111
00:07:21,549 --> 00:07:25,252
number of moves in which to achieve those goals and avoid a failure.

112
00:07:27,020 --> 00:07:30,001
Here's how Toy Blast has done in the approximately three years

113
00:07:30,061 --> 00:07:31,521
that it's been live in the app stores.

114
00:07:32,121 --> 00:07:34,262
Across iPhone, iPad, and Android,

115
00:07:34,302 --> 00:07:35,483
the story is quite similar.

116
00:07:36,123 --> 00:07:37,803
About 1 and 1⁄2 years of growth,

117
00:07:38,183 --> 00:07:40,604
and then 1 and 1⁄2 years comfortably ensconced

118
00:07:40,644 --> 00:07:43,665
in the top 25 grossing across all three major platforms.

119
00:07:45,466 --> 00:07:47,427
Flash forward to about six months ago,

120
00:07:47,867 --> 00:07:50,047
and the release of a second block removal game

121
00:07:50,087 --> 00:07:52,868
by Peak Games, this one called Toon Blast.

122
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:57,062
The core gameplay is almost identical to that in Toy Blast.

123
00:07:58,683 --> 00:08:01,686
Like Toy Blast, Toon Blast is an excellent implementation.

124
00:08:02,306 --> 00:08:05,208
The core gameplay is well made with saturated colors

125
00:08:05,268 --> 00:08:06,769
and satisfying animations.

126
00:08:07,230 --> 00:08:09,171
The levels are well designed and balanced.

127
00:08:09,672 --> 00:08:11,573
The boosts are well tutorialized.

128
00:08:12,093 --> 00:08:14,615
There are plenty of rewards to keep players engaged.

129
00:08:14,976 --> 00:08:16,317
The characters are appealing.

130
00:08:16,717 --> 00:08:19,259
And the monetization is well planned and well executed.

131
00:08:19,779 --> 00:08:22,141
Overall, a solid A-level implementation.

132
00:08:23,706 --> 00:08:26,567
So what has changed from Toy Blast to Toon Blast?

133
00:08:27,747 --> 00:08:28,967
For one thing, there's the theme.

134
00:08:29,467 --> 00:08:31,688
Whereas Toy Blast is set in a child's playroom

135
00:08:32,048 --> 00:08:34,049
and focuses on toys and game pieces,

136
00:08:34,569 --> 00:08:37,349
Toon Blast is set in a classic animation world

137
00:08:37,389 --> 00:08:39,570
of the 20th century, the sort of world

138
00:08:39,630 --> 00:08:42,931
where Bugs Bunny and Wile E. Coyote and Tom and Jerry

139
00:08:42,971 --> 00:08:43,591
would be at home.

140
00:08:44,871 --> 00:08:48,292
These are the main characters, an anthropomorphic bear, wolf,

141
00:08:48,592 --> 00:08:48,932
and cat.

142
00:08:51,527 --> 00:08:56,469
The theme carries over into the level gameplay, with game pieces and power-ups evoking the

143
00:08:56,509 --> 00:08:58,490
world of Roger Rabbit and Toontown.

144
00:09:00,451 --> 00:09:05,093
And sometimes the inspiration for the world of Toonblast is startlingly explicit.

145
00:09:06,814 --> 00:09:12,176
But what's most interesting, and even fascinating about Toonblast, isn't what's there.

146
00:09:13,217 --> 00:09:14,137
It's what isn't there.

147
00:09:16,744 --> 00:09:19,345
Since the introduction of the level-based progression genre

148
00:09:19,625 --> 00:09:22,086
with the King games in the early days of this decade,

149
00:09:22,946 --> 00:09:24,286
would-be entrants into the genre

150
00:09:24,306 --> 00:09:26,447
have closely copied King's saga model,

151
00:09:26,867 --> 00:09:29,128
including a meta-map to organize the levels.

152
00:09:29,928 --> 00:09:31,829
And in fact, Toy Blast had exactly

153
00:09:31,909 --> 00:09:33,589
such a saga-style map shown here.

154
00:09:36,070 --> 00:09:38,571
But Toon Blast has no such map whatsoever.

155
00:09:39,311 --> 00:09:40,611
The only way to enter a level,

156
00:09:41,031 --> 00:09:42,332
and in fact the only way to know

157
00:09:42,352 --> 00:09:43,832
what level you've reached so far,

158
00:09:44,332 --> 00:09:45,933
is this button on your home screen.

159
00:09:46,664 --> 00:09:50,006
There's no map to give you a narrative sense of a journey through an environment.

160
00:09:50,286 --> 00:09:52,648
There's no way to replay a level to get more stars.

161
00:09:52,908 --> 00:09:55,591
There's no way to see your progress versus that of your friends.

162
00:09:56,792 --> 00:10:00,294
It's basically peak games acknowledging that the sort of social interactions

163
00:10:00,334 --> 00:10:04,117
that were born on Facebook Canvas are not operant in the mobile arena

164
00:10:04,538 --> 00:10:05,278
and never will be.

165
00:10:06,539 --> 00:10:07,600
But in subtracting some...

166
00:10:08,441 --> 00:10:08,681
Sorry.

167
00:10:09,522 --> 00:10:13,145
By subtracting something as significant as the saga-style map,

168
00:10:13,785 --> 00:10:14,786
have they added anything?

169
00:10:16,458 --> 00:10:19,540
Yes, this unobtrusive button here,

170
00:10:20,301 --> 00:10:22,842
which takes you to a world of social gameplay.

171
00:10:23,522 --> 00:10:26,124
Casual guilds that Toon Blast calls teams.

172
00:10:26,924 --> 00:10:29,546
You're placed onto such a team with 49 strangers.

173
00:10:30,246 --> 00:10:33,148
No decisions to be made, not even naming your team.

174
00:10:34,308 --> 00:10:35,609
You can chat with your teammates.

175
00:10:35,649 --> 00:10:37,530
You can give them extra lives and hearts.

176
00:10:37,930 --> 00:10:40,512
You can see the stats of the 50 players on your team

177
00:10:40,672 --> 00:10:41,992
in a leaderboard-like layout.

178
00:10:42,993 --> 00:10:44,674
There's a summary of the team's info.

179
00:10:45,536 --> 00:10:48,298
and special events like this team chess challenge,

180
00:10:48,358 --> 00:10:51,080
which is clearly influenced by the less casual clan

181
00:10:51,120 --> 00:10:53,021
gameplay of Clash Royale.

182
00:10:54,242 --> 00:10:57,323
All in all, it's a startling and exciting experiment

183
00:10:57,484 --> 00:10:59,665
in casual social gameplay with strangers.

184
00:11:02,006 --> 00:11:03,247
And the marketplace results?

185
00:11:04,108 --> 00:11:05,549
Within a couple of months of launch,

186
00:11:05,669 --> 00:11:08,471
Toon Blast was showing similar results to Toy Blast,

187
00:11:09,031 --> 00:11:13,033
comfortably embedded in the top 25 grossing lists for all three

188
00:11:13,073 --> 00:11:13,954
major platforms.

189
00:11:17,296 --> 00:11:19,357
The first lesson here is that quality matters.

190
00:11:20,738 --> 00:11:25,480
As I mentioned, Toon Blast isn't just a random level-based progression game innovating on

191
00:11:25,500 --> 00:11:26,401
the metagame wrapper.

192
00:11:27,221 --> 00:11:30,242
It's also a first-rate implementation of a block removal game.

193
00:11:31,843 --> 00:11:33,644
Second is that franchise matters.

194
00:11:34,525 --> 00:11:39,567
Building on the back of the success of Toy Blast, which reached top 25 territory in about

195
00:11:40,047 --> 00:11:44,590
18 months, Toon Blast reached the same level of success in just two or three months.

196
00:11:45,639 --> 00:11:48,240
We've seen this pattern over and over in free-to-play games,

197
00:11:48,700 --> 00:11:52,643
with Zynga's various Vil games, King's various Saga games,

198
00:11:53,463 --> 00:11:56,585
more recently Supercell with nearly instant success

199
00:11:56,645 --> 00:12:01,668
by building Clash Royale on the super successful Clash of Clans franchise,

200
00:12:02,269 --> 00:12:05,190
and Playrix doing the same with the recent release of Homescapes.

201
00:12:08,012 --> 00:12:10,434
And the experimentation on the metagame front

202
00:12:10,954 --> 00:12:15,096
in games like Gummy Drop, Gardenscapes, and now Toon Blast,

203
00:12:15,787 --> 00:12:20,368
shows that lots of different formats are possible when designing the metagame envelopes for these

204
00:12:20,428 --> 00:12:26,689
level-based puzzle games, and that companies are being richly rewarded for those experiments,

205
00:12:27,329 --> 00:12:31,930
or at least for the most well thought out and most well executed of those experiments.

206
00:12:36,872 --> 00:12:44,473
So, since the dawn of human history, we've gathered together to be entertained.

207
00:12:45,187 --> 00:12:48,469
first in a mob all making music or telling stories together.

208
00:12:49,349 --> 00:12:52,031
Then slowly, we spawned professional entertainers

209
00:12:52,071 --> 00:12:53,272
that would get up on stage.

210
00:12:53,432 --> 00:12:55,713
But still, hundreds, thousands of us

211
00:12:55,733 --> 00:12:57,914
would gather together at a time and a place to watch this.

212
00:12:58,835 --> 00:13:00,415
Technology moved us further apart

213
00:13:00,656 --> 00:13:02,477
as we began to record the performers.

214
00:13:02,857 --> 00:13:04,538
But still, we would huddle together

215
00:13:04,618 --> 00:13:07,739
by the hundreds in theaters to see these great performances

216
00:13:07,779 --> 00:13:08,740
played over and over.

217
00:13:10,321 --> 00:13:11,822
This began to fragment further.

218
00:13:12,218 --> 00:13:16,801
in the middle of the last century as television came into the home and the viewing group moved

219
00:13:16,821 --> 00:13:19,764
from hundreds of people together to a small family.

220
00:13:20,664 --> 00:13:26,489
And then as we got DVRs and VCRs allowing us to watch our individual programs separately

221
00:13:26,589 --> 00:13:28,411
when we wanted them on our own schedule.

222
00:13:29,071 --> 00:13:36,157
Now streaming services like Netflix and Hulu bring the entire history of film and TV into

223
00:13:36,217 --> 00:13:38,719
our homes when we want them and onto our phones as we want them.

224
00:13:39,399 --> 00:13:40,840
And it's not just that way with movies.

225
00:13:41,465 --> 00:13:43,106
Consuming news has gone the same way.

226
00:13:43,526 --> 00:13:47,228
Solo where you want, so has music and even games.

227
00:13:49,369 --> 00:13:52,570
So I ask you, is this a one-way street?

228
00:13:53,690 --> 00:13:58,032
Is there nothing that can reverse this trend of how we consume media?

229
00:13:59,253 --> 00:14:00,593
It turns out the answer is...

230
00:14:02,834 --> 00:14:03,194
HQ.

231
00:14:05,615 --> 00:14:08,976
It's a recently released game from the original makers of Vine,

232
00:14:08,997 --> 00:14:10,597
the 15-second video sharing app.

233
00:14:11,182 --> 00:14:14,645
For those of you who haven't seen it, it's a trivia game.

234
00:14:14,685 --> 00:14:16,646
It presents users with a series of questions.

235
00:14:17,647 --> 00:14:19,768
Questions are read out by a live host,

236
00:14:20,428 --> 00:14:23,050
and then players have only a few seconds to answer them,

237
00:14:23,130 --> 00:14:25,032
to prevent them from Googling the answer.

238
00:14:25,872 --> 00:14:27,513
The content is very well crafted.

239
00:14:28,314 --> 00:14:30,595
Over the course of the game, the difficulty ramps up from

240
00:14:32,617 --> 00:14:37,300
trivial to excruciatingly difficult and obscure.

241
00:14:37,920 --> 00:14:39,041
The answer, by the way, is Twister.

242
00:14:42,552 --> 00:14:47,373
Every question feels momentous. You miss a single question and you're out of the game.

243
00:14:47,433 --> 00:14:52,614
