522
00:27:57,866 --> 00:28:00,067
of interactive story games on the App Store.

523
00:28:01,467 --> 00:28:04,209
These games are to some extent the spiritual successor

524
00:28:04,729 --> 00:28:06,650
of the sorts of choose-your-own-path novels

525
00:28:06,710 --> 00:28:08,290
that perhaps some of you grew up reading.

526
00:28:10,191 --> 00:28:12,152
The app that started this trend was Episode,

527
00:28:12,632 --> 00:28:14,493
from San Francisco-based Pocket Gems.

528
00:28:15,813 --> 00:28:18,555
It's not really a game, it's not really a story.

529
00:28:19,275 --> 00:28:22,536
What it is, is a platform for creating and dispensing

530
00:28:22,716 --> 00:28:24,217
any number of interactive stories.

531
00:28:25,510 --> 00:28:29,812
Thematically, these stories fill into the soap opera or romance novel category,

532
00:28:30,272 --> 00:28:34,335
with high school or college settings and lots and lots of dating drama.

533
00:28:36,496 --> 00:28:40,398
Almost every story begins with you customizing the appearance of the main character.

534
00:28:40,999 --> 00:28:45,141
This is the part of the story with the greatest amount of interactivity.

535
00:28:46,502 --> 00:28:51,425
Once you're past that avatar customization, the stories tend to have long stretches with no agency.

536
00:28:51,983 --> 00:28:56,907
and with no interactivity beyond just tapping to get to the next line of dialogue or to the next scene.

537
00:28:58,329 --> 00:29:01,491
Occasionally, on average, I'd say less than once per minute,

538
00:29:01,991 --> 00:29:05,554
you get to make a choice that will actually have some kind of impact on the story.

539
00:29:07,136 --> 00:29:09,117
This is also how episode monetizes.

540
00:29:09,618 --> 00:29:12,080
Some of these choices have a cost associated with them.

541
00:29:13,020 --> 00:29:19,185
Typically, the most dramatic, most salacious, and most revenge fantasy oriented of your choices.

542
00:29:21,461 --> 00:29:23,823
The choice displayed here would cost you roughly $2.

543
00:29:23,943 --> 00:29:27,906
These are almost like pay-to-play moments,

544
00:29:28,027 --> 00:29:31,550
because the choices are so stark between do something exciting

545
00:29:32,130 --> 00:29:33,191
and do nothing at all.

546
00:29:34,752 --> 00:29:37,114
It's as if, when you were approaching Emerald City,

547
00:29:37,274 --> 00:29:39,656
the choices were enter and see the wizard,

548
00:29:41,118 --> 00:29:42,919
or just continue to wander aimlessly

549
00:29:42,959 --> 00:29:44,080
around the forests of Oz.

550
00:29:47,047 --> 00:29:51,668
The game also monetizes by selling chapters using a currency called passes.

551
00:29:52,409 --> 00:29:57,530
Like energy in Mafia Wars or Hearts in Candy Crush, you get a trickle of free passes over

552
00:29:57,590 --> 00:29:57,871
time.

553
00:29:59,651 --> 00:30:04,293
A pass can be purchased for about 30 cents, which lets you play one chapter.

554
00:30:05,894 --> 00:30:07,034
Or read one chapter.

555
00:30:07,354 --> 00:30:08,755
I'm not really sure what the right verb is.

556
00:30:11,498 --> 00:30:15,681
There are original stories, but there are also plenty of stories that use branded IP,

557
00:30:15,981 --> 00:30:19,664
such as movies like Pitch Perfect or celebrities like Demi Lovato.

558
00:30:21,104 --> 00:30:26,868
The platform also allows for user-created stories, with mechanisms like voting and contests

559
00:30:26,968 --> 00:30:31,291
to surface the best-written and highest-quality stories to the episode community.

560
00:30:32,491 --> 00:30:37,955
These user-created stories feature information screens and author profiles, so authors can

561
00:30:38,015 --> 00:30:39,776
even start to develop their own following.

562
00:30:41,300 --> 00:30:46,444
These user-created stories allow for much broader sets of experiences and interests,

563
00:30:46,925 --> 00:30:50,948
such as this user-created story that features a character who is a mute Muslim woman.

564
00:30:52,870 --> 00:30:55,752
And what is the performance of Episode in the App Store?

565
00:30:57,594 --> 00:31:00,516
The results on Android and on the iPad are only middling.

566
00:31:01,077 --> 00:31:03,799
The game has rarely broken into the top 50 grossing.

567
00:31:04,940 --> 00:31:09,063
But it's a totally different story on iPhone, where the game took a while to find its market

568
00:31:09,495 --> 00:31:13,196
but since late 2015 has been consistently in the top 25,

569
00:31:13,736 --> 00:31:15,096
peaking as high as seventh.

570
00:31:16,017 --> 00:31:18,257
Clearly the younger skewing audience for this game

571
00:31:18,317 --> 00:31:19,758
is a much more phone-oriented

572
00:31:19,798 --> 00:31:21,238
than tablet-oriented audience.

573
00:31:23,219 --> 00:31:26,720
Then in mid-2016, Episode got a major competitor

574
00:31:26,740 --> 00:31:29,120
in the form of Choices, Stories You Play,

575
00:31:29,740 --> 00:31:31,801
from Mountain View-based Pixelberry Studios.

576
00:31:33,581 --> 00:31:35,802
Choices is closely modeled after Episode

577
00:31:36,262 --> 00:31:38,263
with similar multi-story homepage.

578
00:31:38,880 --> 00:31:44,766
a similar intro to each story chapter, similar start-of-game character customization, similar

579
00:31:44,806 --> 00:31:50,071
pacing of linear dialogues interrupted only occasionally by actual decision points, and

580
00:31:50,111 --> 00:31:55,155
an identical monetization scheme via paying for the juiciest decisions or currency to

581
00:31:55,215 --> 00:31:56,116
unlock new chapters.

582
00:31:57,497 --> 00:32:01,161
One difference is that Choices lacks the branded story content of Episode.

583
00:32:02,495 --> 00:32:07,598
It also has an achievement system which can give the app a somewhat stronger feeling of

584
00:32:07,638 --> 00:32:08,778
a gameplay experience.

585
00:32:10,299 --> 00:32:12,600
So how is Choices doing compared to Episode?

586
00:32:14,001 --> 00:32:19,044
The grossing charts look almost identical, middling results on Android, which combines

587
00:32:19,124 --> 00:32:26,168
smartphone and tablet numbers onto a single chart, and unimpressive numbers on iPad, but

588
00:32:26,268 --> 00:32:27,708
excellent numbers on iPhone.

589
00:32:28,901 --> 00:32:33,384
As with episode, Choices has been firmly planted in the top 25 for the past year.

590
00:32:34,425 --> 00:32:38,268
Of course, while it took episode a couple of years to work its way into the top 25,

591
00:32:38,368 --> 00:32:40,009
Choices did it in about six months.

592
00:32:41,350 --> 00:32:46,373
This parody and performance is pretty startling, given how imitative Choices is of episode.

593
00:32:47,875 --> 00:32:51,697
In the past, we've seen imitative games come in and dominate their predecessors, such as

594
00:32:52,198 --> 00:32:55,960
World of Warcraft over EverQuest, or Candy Crush in the wake of Bejewelled.

595
00:32:56,381 --> 00:33:00,544
But in these cases, the successor games were clearly improvements on the games that came before.

596
00:33:01,245 --> 00:33:05,088
Choices doesn't seem to be a clear improvement on Episode in any obvious way.

597
00:33:06,549 --> 00:33:10,732
One possible explanation, Pocket Gems, in addition to their Episode business,

598
00:33:10,872 --> 00:33:14,195
has also been working on a major mid-core mobile game called War Dragons.

599
00:33:14,975 --> 00:33:19,359
It may be that this divided focus caused them to take their eye off the interactive story ball,

600
00:33:19,639 --> 00:33:22,161
whereas Pixelberry, with no other focus, took advantage.

601
00:33:23,664 --> 00:33:28,787
In fact, Pixelberry parlayed the successive choices into an acquisition by Correa's Nexon

602
00:33:29,307 --> 00:33:31,549
this past November for an undisclosed sum.

603
00:33:33,190 --> 00:33:38,033
And with episode and choices both making good money, the ranks are swelling with similar

604
00:33:38,093 --> 00:33:38,554
offerings.

605
00:33:39,754 --> 00:33:44,798
First up is My Story from Nanobit, then Luvstruck from Voltage.

606
00:33:45,518 --> 00:33:49,721
As you can see, this game is in landscape mode, which in this category counts as rampant

607
00:33:49,761 --> 00:33:50,122
innovation.

608
00:33:53,742 --> 00:33:55,503
Ludia released What's Your Story?

609
00:33:57,343 --> 00:33:59,624
Then Chapters from Crazy Maple Studio.

610
00:34:01,365 --> 00:34:05,526
And most recently from NTT Solmar, the not at all subtly named

611
00:34:05,927 --> 00:34:08,527
My Shelf, My Choice, My Episode.

612
00:34:13,489 --> 00:34:17,050
So the easy success of Choices seems to indicate that the market for these

613
00:34:17,090 --> 00:34:20,072
sorts of interactive story games is still far from saturated.

614
00:34:20,779 --> 00:34:24,221
Although that might be changing with the flood of post-choices clones.

615
00:34:26,202 --> 00:34:30,185
As a designer, it's amazing to me how much affinity there is for games like these that

616
00:34:30,225 --> 00:34:33,807
have so little interactivity and so little player agency.

617
00:34:34,527 --> 00:34:39,450
Not just a willingness to play games with such a low cadence of interaction, but a willingness

618
00:34:39,490 --> 00:34:42,152
to pay for games with such a low cadence.

619
00:34:42,932 --> 00:34:47,795
I wonder what other genres we could dial down the cadence of interactivity without affecting

620
00:34:47,855 --> 00:34:48,756
player satisfaction.

621
00:34:50,797 --> 00:34:55,418
And finally, more of a prediction than a lesson, we've seen very little variation

622
00:34:55,858 --> 00:35:00,180
among the games in this segment, all of which have pretty much been blindly following the

623
00:35:00,220 --> 00:35:01,520
original episode formula.

624
00:35:02,120 --> 00:35:06,842
But as this market gets more crowded, publishers are going to need to innovate to differentiate

625
00:35:06,882 --> 00:35:10,583
themselves, and I predict that over the next year or two we're going to see some pretty

626
00:35:10,623 --> 00:35:12,143
interesting developments in this genre.

627
00:35:19,605 --> 00:35:23,568
I'd like to say a few words about Golf Clash.

628
00:35:24,889 --> 00:35:28,471
Now, this may come as a bit of a shock,

629
00:35:28,571 --> 00:35:31,793
but Golf Clash is a golf game

630
00:35:32,294 --> 00:35:34,435
from a company called Playdemic,

631
00:35:34,495 --> 00:35:36,176
recently acquired by Warner Brothers.

632
00:35:38,037 --> 00:35:40,619
In the main mode of play, you choose a course

633
00:35:41,480 --> 00:35:44,342
and get matched up against a random opponent

634
00:35:44,362 --> 00:35:46,143
to play a single hole of golf.

635
00:35:48,080 --> 00:35:50,281
As you start, you're taken to an overhead view,

636
00:35:50,862 --> 00:35:54,104
and you have an extremely intuitive shot-making interface.

637
00:35:54,664 --> 00:35:58,647
You drag the targeting reticule to aim your shot,

638
00:35:59,587 --> 00:36:00,808
tap the take shot button,

639
00:36:02,529 --> 00:36:04,690
and then you go down to a golfer's eye view,

640
00:36:04,911 --> 00:36:07,172
you drag the ball backwards to set force

641
00:36:07,412 --> 00:36:08,713
and a little bit of additional spin,

642
00:36:09,454 --> 00:36:11,595
and then try and release your finger

643
00:36:11,795 --> 00:36:14,277
just as the bouncing arrow goes over the center

644
00:36:14,297 --> 00:36:16,118
of the target to shoot it as straight as possible.

645
00:36:16,994 --> 00:36:19,955
The physics feel great, the graphics look gorgeous,

646
00:36:20,556 --> 00:36:22,957
the game plays well, it's a great experience,

647
00:36:22,977 --> 00:36:24,537
and that continues on to the putting green,

648
00:36:25,198 --> 00:36:28,199
where once again it's got the best putting interface

649
00:36:28,239 --> 00:36:30,500
of any golf game I've played on any platform.

650
00:36:31,160 --> 00:36:33,281
Simple and direct, drag the ball down

651
00:36:33,561 --> 00:36:35,622
to set direction and to set force.

652
00:36:36,343 --> 00:36:37,843
The blue vector comes out the front.

653
00:36:38,964 --> 00:36:40,104
When you're gonna get it in the hole,

654
00:36:40,484 --> 00:36:42,425
the hole lights up, the flag pops out,

655
00:36:42,765 --> 00:36:44,866
and then once again you play the bouncing arrow game

656
00:36:45,547 --> 00:36:46,807
to try and get it straight in.

657
00:36:50,562 --> 00:36:54,564
The player who gets the ball in the hole in the fewest shots wins the match.

658
00:36:56,145 --> 00:36:58,587
If you tie, there's a one-shot playoff.

659
00:36:58,667 --> 00:37:07,113
Whoever hits it closest to the hole gets some gold that's contributed from players' entry

660
00:37:07,153 --> 00:37:08,414
fees, some soft currency.

661
00:37:09,475 --> 00:37:12,397
So why is this game worth talking about?

662
00:37:12,657 --> 00:37:14,598
We've seen casual sports titles before.

663
00:37:14,618 --> 00:37:19,001
8-ball pull from Miniclip has been a fixture in the top 50 for

664
00:37:19,984 --> 00:37:25,648
years. And they had some reasonable success with Archery King and Bowling King as well.

665
00:37:27,689 --> 00:37:35,875
Well, what is it that makes Golf Clash worth our attention? It has a very interesting metagame.

666
00:37:37,496 --> 00:37:42,039
So in Golf Clash, when you win a match, you gain trophies. When you lose a match, you

667
00:37:42,079 --> 00:37:47,882
lose trophies. And you unlock access to new courses based on the number of trophies you

668
00:37:47,943 --> 00:37:48,243
have.

669
00:37:50,431 --> 00:37:53,713
To play the game, you need to decide which clubs you're going to use.

670
00:37:53,753 --> 00:37:56,855
You need to make the right collection to suit your play style.

671
00:37:58,736 --> 00:38:03,479
And you get access to different clubs by grinding your way through different courses.

672
00:38:05,960 --> 00:38:10,022
Each club has a variety of statistics that make it play quite differently from the other

673
00:38:10,062 --> 00:38:16,066
clubs in its class, and you can upgrade them to increase their performance using the soft

674
00:38:16,126 --> 00:38:18,007
currency that you win from winning matches.

675
00:38:18,990 --> 00:38:20,911
and cards you get from opening chests.

676
00:38:23,032 --> 00:38:24,192
Where do these chests come from?

677
00:38:24,272 --> 00:38:26,433
Why, you get one when you win a match.

678
00:38:27,354 --> 00:38:30,095
And then you insert it into one of four chest slots

679
00:38:30,215 --> 00:38:32,817
where you start a timer to open it later.

680
00:38:32,897 --> 00:38:36,258
And you can also get free chests every four hours

681
00:38:36,418 --> 00:38:40,160
and every eight holes that you get it in.

682
00:38:40,180 --> 00:38:42,561
I don't know.

683
00:38:44,095 --> 00:38:50,920
It all seems oddly familiar somehow. Where could I have seen this before? Could there be some game

684
00:38:50,960 --> 00:38:56,204
where you win and lose trophies through play and use that to unlock new, you know, new battlegrounds

685
00:38:56,304 --> 00:39:02,189
and assemble collections of units to suit your play style that you get by reaching arenas and

686
00:39:02,269 --> 00:39:09,714
upgrade them with money and cards and get chests and put them in chest slots? Huh.

687
00:39:12,095 --> 00:39:18,097
Yeah, Clash Royale. I mean, come on, people. They actually took half the name, right?

688
00:39:18,457 --> 00:39:23,318
Just the metagame wasn't good enough. Now, that's not to say it's completely derivative.

689
00:39:23,378 --> 00:39:28,640
They did some really smart things to adapt the meta to their golf game. They have golf balls,

690
00:39:28,680 --> 00:39:34,021
which are consumable goods. You use a ball that has extra power or wind resistance on a hole,

691
00:39:34,181 --> 00:39:38,722
and then it's gone. They have a nice multi-round tournament structure.

692
00:39:39,123 --> 00:39:41,704
that emulates the structure of real-world golf tournaments.

693
00:39:41,724 --> 00:39:43,785
You have to qualify to play in the opening rounds

694
00:39:43,845 --> 00:39:44,686
to play in the finals.

695
00:39:46,007 --> 00:39:48,748
They do a great offer of constantly surfacing

696
00:39:48,868 --> 00:39:51,710
great value deals for cash to add to monetization.

697
00:39:53,190 --> 00:39:56,152
They also threw away the mid-core clans of Clash Royale

698
00:39:56,232 --> 00:39:57,453
and replaced them with simpler

699
00:39:57,593 --> 00:39:59,234
and more casual social structures.

700
00:40:01,475 --> 00:40:04,016
Like Facebook-style gifting of soft currency

701
00:40:04,096 --> 00:40:05,717
and golf balls and a few gems.

702
00:40:06,662 --> 00:40:09,284
And also, every week, they place you into a league

703
00:40:09,624 --> 00:40:12,727
with 99 random strangers at the same level of accomplishment.

704
00:40:13,648 --> 00:40:15,549
At the end of the week, the 25 top players

705
00:40:15,589 --> 00:40:17,231
get promoted into the next highest league

706
00:40:17,371 --> 00:40:19,393
and get better bonuses when they open their chests.

707
00:40:20,674 --> 00:40:25,258
But really, at its core, it's extremely similar

708
00:40:25,298 --> 00:40:26,579
to the Clash Royale metagame.

709
00:40:27,259 --> 00:40:30,122
Now, this is not the first time we've seen a metagame lifted

710
00:40:30,462 --> 00:40:31,423
on the App Store, right?

711
00:40:32,404 --> 00:40:34,225
How many puzzle games have shown you

712
00:40:34,955 --> 00:40:38,437
a reskin of this exact Candy Crush saga map.

713
00:40:39,318 --> 00:40:40,459
Dozens if not hundreds.

714
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:45,363
How many RPGs have shown you this exact

715
00:40:45,763 --> 00:40:48,485
hero upgrade screen from Heroes Charge?

716
00:40:49,706 --> 00:40:51,067
Answer, all of them.

717
00:40:52,968 --> 00:40:56,531
But these guys have had huge success

718
00:40:56,551 --> 00:40:57,732
within their own genres.

719
00:40:58,192 --> 00:41:00,594
Golf Clash is one of the first examples we've seen

720
00:41:00,654 --> 00:41:02,996
of a complete metagame transplant.

721
00:41:03,653 --> 00:41:05,793
from one genre, real-time strategy,

722
00:41:06,553 --> 00:41:09,434
into a completely different one, casual sports.

723
00:41:10,454 --> 00:41:11,815
And it's been done to great effect.

724
00:41:12,795 --> 00:41:14,535
As you can see, after a period of growth,

725
00:41:15,355 --> 00:41:20,896
the game has stayed in the top 25 on Android and on iPhone.

726
00:41:21,657 --> 00:41:23,357
It hasn't performed as well on tablet,

727
00:41:24,157 --> 00:41:26,758
perhaps because the game is so friendly

728
00:41:26,818 --> 00:41:28,618
to those little two or three-minute windows

729
00:41:28,658 --> 00:41:30,718
you find yourself with throughout the day with your phone.

730
00:41:32,630 --> 00:41:33,751
So what can we learn from this?

731
00:41:35,111 --> 00:41:39,392
We now have a second proof point for casual sports taking up

732
00:41:39,432 --> 00:41:41,152
habitual residence in the top 50.

733
00:41:42,012 --> 00:41:44,913
This is a category that the App Store has some appetite for.

734
00:41:46,513 --> 00:41:49,734
Number two, the Clash Royale metagame

735
00:41:50,114 --> 00:41:52,774
has joined the lexicon of highly portable metagames.

736
00:41:53,034 --> 00:41:55,575
It belongs in every mobile game designer's toolkit

737
00:41:56,315 --> 00:41:59,275
and has shown great resilience moving from genre to genre.

738
00:42:00,623 --> 00:42:04,524
And third, the market doesn't really seem to be punishing this adaptation

739
00:42:05,205 --> 00:42:07,545
because of a few things that Golf Clash has done,

740
00:42:07,986 --> 00:42:12,847
like build a great core game with fantastic usability, great physics,

741
00:42:13,488 --> 00:42:15,028
really fun and satisfying to play.

742
00:42:16,689 --> 00:42:18,829
They've integrated the metagame very smartly.

743
00:42:19,150 --> 00:42:19,930
It's meaningful.

744
00:42:20,050 --> 00:42:21,831
